Below is the complete Kubernetes deployment guide for your Flask Registration App built from the previous Docker image (flask-registration).

1. Prerequisites

Before proceeding, ensure:

Docker image is already built and (optionally) pushed to Docker Hub.

Kubernetes is installed (e.g., via Minikube or Docker Desktop).

kubectl command-line tool is configured.

2. Push Image to Docker Hub (if using Kubernetes on another machine)
# Log in to Docker Hub
docker login

# Tag the image for Docker Hub
docker tag flask-registration <your-dockerhub-username>/flask-registration:latest

# Push the image
docker push <your-dockerhub-username>/flask-registration:latest

3. Create Kubernetes Deployment File

Create a file named deployment.yaml in your project folder.

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: flask-registration-deployment
  labels:
    app: flask-registration
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: flask-registration
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: flask-registration
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: flask-registration-container
        image: <your-dockerhub-username>/flask-registration:latest
        ports:
        - containerPort: 5000
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: flask-registration-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: flask-registration
  ports:
  - protocol: TCP
    port: 80
    targetPort: 5000
  type: NodePort


Replace <your-dockerhub-username> with your actual Docker Hub username.

4. Deploy on Kubernetes
# Apply deployment and service files
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

5. Verify the Pod and Service Status
# Check if pods are running
kubectl get pods

# Check deployment status
kubectl get deployments

# Check services
kubectl get svc


Expected Output Example:

NAME                                 READY   STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE
flask-registration-deployment-abcde   1/1     Running   0          1m
flask-registration-deployment-fghij   1/1     Running   0          1m

6. Access the Flask Application

If using Minikube, run:

minikube service flask-registration-service


This will open the Flask registration form in your browser (default port usually http://<minikube-ip>:<nodePort>).

If using Docker Desktop Kubernetes, note the NodePort using:

kubectl get svc


Then visit:

http://localhost:<nodePort>

7. Clean Up Resources

To delete everything created:

kubectl delete -f deployment.yaml
